    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Neptune's atmosphere is characterized by abundant CO, which origin is not unveiled yet. Cometary origin is the most possible source. To verify that hypothesis, authors have performed survey observations of Sulfur-bearing species since 2010. Since S-bearing species are contained abundant in comet, some form of S-bearing species should be present in the upper stratosphere of Neptune. From the chemical model analysis, extracted possible S-bearing species were CS, H2CS and H2S. In turn, from our observations, no S-bearing species was detected and their upper limit abundance was quite lower than expected. However derived upper limit of H2S was higher than typical S/O value of small solar system bodies due to the technical difficulties of single-dish observations. From the non-detection result of CS and H2CS, H2S is implied as an only possible candidate. In addition, we derived that H2S can exist in gas phase and observable. ALMA is the only facility which can observe H2S even if its abundance is in lower limit. Thus, we request H2S observation on Neptune to verify the cometary origin hypothesis perfectly.</prp:abstract>
